She flipped to a blank page and wrote the date on it. Then, she wrote below the date: "5/11/648-12/13/648".
"Are you looking back on the past?" Avery asked, looking at the old notebook. Carly nodded. "Do you think they'll let you go out for Christmas? There are only a few days left until Christmas."
Carly tapped the lantern twice, indicating "no." As Avery had expected. The Ice King never allowed Carly to go out, because in his eyes, Carly was "a flaw." Carly was born a mute and was the only girl in the family; the other children were all boys.
Avery was the same, in their own unique way. When Avery came out as non-binary, the world seemed to change as well. As a punishment for their uniqueness, they were assigned to work alone for most of the time.
They were also forced to be the princess's servant. But they didn't mind, because they had a friend.
"Your birthday is coming up, right?" Avery asked, remembering that Princess's birthday was just a few days away. Carly nodded, a hint of sadness flashing in her light blue eyes.
"Do you want to celebrate?" Avery asked, recalling how Carly had answered this question last time.
No. Carly tapped the table. Avery knew this was a difficult topic for Carly to speak about. On this very day, she was trapped in this room, while her mother was executed. When it happened, Avery was still an infant, but TA remembered the anger of the servants and citizens at the time. TA had heard that Queen Elwin was a good queen, and could even predict future events.
"So... what do you want to do?" Avery asked. Carly looked up at Avery, excited. She handed Avery a piece of paper. However, when he looked down...
6-inch X 6-inch canvas
White, varying shades of blue paint
6 brushes of different sizes
An easel
"Are you trying to get me to bring you these things?" Avery turned to the silent princess, who was constantly tapping and her ponytail swaying back and forth. "Is that right?" When TA saw the usually quiet princess so enthusiastic about something, TA couldn't help but giggle. This was the first time she wanted something outside of her room, and it wasn't related to books.
"Okay! See you later?" Avery said, standing up and walking through the messy papers and notebooks.
Carly nodded and continued to burrow deeper into the thick blankets, recalling her memories.
As TA stepped out of the room, thinking about the princess finally being willing to try new things and making requests beyond TA's ability (such as paint), TA felt relieved.
TA passed through the hall again, trying not to pay attention to the servants' whispers.
"I heard she was possessed by Queen Elwin, so she always went to that room."
"I heard she ate children in that room."
"Does she look like a man? Is that normal?"
TA couldn't stand the words anymore, so TA covered his ears. TA went to the room of the royal painter, which was in the eastern wing, the second door on the left.
Avery arrived at that door, which was just like Carly's door, beautifully decorated. The door was painted with a white dragon, one of the six original dragons, said to have created the Frost Kingdom. The painter liked history, so it was no surprise that the white dragon was painted on the door.
TA opened the door, expecting everything to be as usual. For example, there were paints everywhere, pencils and papers scattered around, and the easel covered every inch of the walls. But to TA's surprise, the scene inside the room was completely different. The room was clean, with a red velvet backdrop and a chair. The chair was occupied by Prince Aquiro, who was painting a portrait.
"Ah, good morning, Avery! Want to see the portrait of your future king?" Aquiro asked, and winked at Avery.
"Sorry, Your Highness," TA replied, starting to search around for the things Princess Carly wanted. "I'm just here to get some art supplies."
"Little darling, are you leaving so quickly?" Aquiro asked, "But I still want to meet you!"
"I don't want to," Avery found the art supplies on the list and put them into a box. "And I'm not a girl."
The prince didn't take it seriously. "Oh, darling, you know this is just a phase! It'll be fine when you grow up!" he said vaguely.
"I have to go," TA said, suddenly feeling uncomfortable because the prince was still talking nonstop. TA recalled all the negative comments people had about TA's gender identity. I really want to get away from him."
"Are you leaving so soon?" The prince suddenly appeared at the door, ignoring the royal painter's shout.
"This is not the behavior of a future king!" TA shouted fiercely.
"No one will know. People won't believe you, and if that painter still values his life, he wouldn't have spoken out like that." The prince turned back to look at the painter, then leaned in close to Avery. "What do you think about going on a date?" TA shivered in fear. Of course, TA had heard many threats before, but these threats were never from the prince, let alone the future king.
"Do you even know what 'no' means?" TA shouted, pushing the prince away forcefully.
"No." Aquiro smiled and answered. This prince, who could get anything he wanted, obviously didn't know what 'no' meant.
Avery rolled her eyes. "Why so many people, and you just want to go on a date with me? How many suitors do you have? A hundred?"
He laughed and interrupted. "Actually, over five hundred." He shook his hair, letting it sway in the cold wind.
"See? Why me? I'm the curse of the palace." TA hugged her arms.
"You are the most beautiful girl I have ever seen." Aquiro placed a finger under Avery's chin, forcing her to look up at him.
